This demo code is tested with Vagrant 1.0.2 and VirtualBox 4.1.10.

This is a simple example of how to build a virtual test environment with Vagrant and Puppet.

The setup contains two Centos 5.8 (64 bit) virtual machines, one database server with MySQL and one application server with Tomcat 6.

Simply check it out, chdir into the directory and then run

> vagrant up

to start the two boxes.

Note: If you're on Windows, its likely you'll need to set up SSH properly.  See: http://docs-v1.vagrantup.com/v1/docs/getting-started/ssh.html

Note: If you're behind a firewall, then Vagrant won't be able to able to see the box to download it.  Set an environment property to fix this: "export HTTP_PROXY="host:port"

You'll then have your application server at http://33.33.33.10:8080 and your database server listens on 33.33.33.11. Enjoy!

When you're done, don't forget to stop your virtual boxes with

> vagrant halt

or completely remove them with

> vagrant destroy

NOTE: To get things working smoothly, you'll need to:
* Increase the VM memory (and CPU) of the VNM image (do this via the VirtualBox "settings" menu item once you've run the VM for the first time
